I don't believe that at this point there is any change of retreat or diplomacy to prevent armed conflict. Putin wants what he wants and is determined to get it. In his address this morning, the said there is room for diplomacy but listed 3 items that will need to be agreed to: non expansion of NATO, non deployment of weapons next to Russian border, bring back military infrastructure to the 1997 proposal, and he said they'd need to be approved as a package. I don't believe NATO alliance or the US will agree to that. Putin has already ordered Russian "peace keeping forces" into Ukraine's separatist regions.

Even though there will be no winners if serious fighting breaks out, and there will be many serious losers, things are looking pretty grim. If Putin actually initiates hostilities, then he will truly deserve the reality-check coming his way next. He may well soon lose everything. Here’s hoping that basic common sense and diplomacy can still somehow prevail.
The 21. February acknowledgement of DPR and LPR is a likely precursor for deployment of Russian forces as "peace keepers" and thus makes an ensuing military conflict more propable.
With tensions riding it's likely there will combat resulting in deaths.

This is denied by Kyiv and the question should not be resolved upon Russian state propaganda. The only real constraint upon Putin is Russian sentiment https://www.levada.ru/en/ If you watch Russian media there is wall to wall coverage of the genocide in Dombass. The Russian people will not be fooled and if fooled cannot be fooled for long. Putin has lived in a bubble for 2 years. He maybe so impaired and disconnected from reality by yes men that he will actually invade beyond cease fire lines. For sure he has occupied Belarus merging that country effectively with Russia and has blockaded Ukraine and now almost certainly will recognize Luhansk and Donestk. All without sanctions. Every signal indicates he will invade ..so why not now? I puzzle on delay His forces are mobilized the pretextual justications are in place and he is selling Russian people hard. Meanwhile the rouble and stock market tank. On balance unless he can make his narrative compelling to the Russian people and so far he has not, he will not invade. Putin maybe the head of a criminal syndicate of Oligarchs but on matters of war and peace he is constrained by public opinion He may find that attempting to reconstruct the vestiges of Russian imperial rule causes him to lose his own empire. My bet is that he will not risk his present kingdom. In the end he is the greatest threat to Russian peace and security as well as his own regime. War is an uncertain arbiter of disputes and for Putin to risk his regime on a massive invasion of Ukraine is risky and irrational. One has to wonder if Putin has become so deluded by his own propaganda megalomania and insular bubble that he will invade. The signals are that he will but the absence of a groundswell of public opinion is conspicuous by silence.

Russian military action will take place soon, putting Russian military forces in direct confrontation with Ukrainian military forces. 207 days left until the question closes, which provides a great deal of time for the event in question to occur. One or two deaths every two or three days. The UN OSCE Special Monitoring Mission to Ukraine daily reports show a dramatic increase in both ceasefire violations and explosions over the past three days. Whether from an "oops" encounter, or from Russian shelling of populated areas, it's only a matter of time.
Another shelling, even more intense. Donetsk and Luhansk evacuate families from the area to Russia. Putin ordered to pay 10,000 rubles to each refugee. Invasion is almost certain.

The false flag event (according to the US & UK) at a school, the increase in shelling from both sides, and the rhetoric from world leaders regarding an 'imminent' & 'inevitable' invasion all increase the likelihood of an attack. Due to weather, if Russia wants to invade they have an incentive to do so as soon as conditions are good enough - right about now. This ideal weather period will likely end around March/beginning of April time.

Beginning to realize that basing the estimate of probability solely on the most recent news stories is an imperfect forecasting strategy given the inconsistency of the analyses. This is obviously a complex and fluid situation. The previous observations notwithstanding, the most recent news suggests the Russians again have become more open to dialogue and conciliation, despite their actions indicating they are continuing to prepare for conflict. I'll slightly lower my probability of confrontation.
Putin starting to withdraw some troops, and diplomatic channels continue to be open

“President Vladimir V. Putin said on Tuesday that Russia had decided “to partially pull back troops” as the Defense Ministry announced that some forces from military districts bordering Ukraine were being sent back to their garrisons, a tentative sign that Russia could be stepping away from the threat of an invasion“

Based on analysis here https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1397893 and this development:

The foreign minister, Sergei Lavrov, declared that the West’s response to Russia’s demands was disappointing, at times even insulting. But it had been shaken by Russia’s actions, Mr Lavrov noted, and America, in particular, had responded positively to at least some demands, notably over arms control in Europe. Talks could not drag on, but he “recommended” intensifying diplomatic contacts. “It seems to me that our possibilities are far from exhausted,” he declared, to approval from Mr Putin. Shortly thereafter Sergei Shoigu, the defence minister, said that some of Russia’s military exercises had ended and others were close to completion.

The press is making noises about how everyone (Putin, Biden, Zelensky and the Europeans) are assuring everyone that a negotiated settlement is still possible. So if Putin gets Western and Ukrainian recognition of Russian annexation of Crimea and the Donbas, plus is given a land corridor between them (which is probably what he wanted all along) both sides can claim that diplomacy has triumphed.
Economic and political consequences for Russia are too dire. Ukraine would not willingly initiate such a confrontation due to numerically superior and more heavily armed Russian forces.
Russia's refusal of a meeting with Ukraine now makes war appear even likelier.

Unlikely. This Russia - Ukraine war is the propaganda brain child of the misguided US administration. If we remember that the son of the US president was working for a Ukrainian gas company (Burisma), then the whole "conflict" suddenly comes back in a different light. Russia had been exercising its military near the Ukrainian border ever since the collapse of the USSR - there is nothing extraordinary in this Winter testing of how ready the military is. The unfortunate media coverage the US administration of this otherwise normal military exercise is creating a hysteria. Both unfortunate and rather damaging. As a side-note, this conflict propelled the US to the No.1. position of LNG exporters in the World: now US gas companies, plus LNG tankers are exporting LNG to Europe with a surplus profit.
Tensions are high but I don’t think Russia’s goal is to invade Ukraine. Ukraine seems cautious not to try to re-take Donbas by force too.

Indicators for an imminent military incursion have increased (weapons handling in Black Sea fleet naval facilities, heavy military helicopter activity near the border, BTG's being moved closer to border). Therefore I am slightly upping the probability. Today's negotiations between Biden and Putin have not seemed to make a big difference, and still de-escalation without military action would require major concessions of which there is no sign of

Russia has built up it's forces near Ukraine since the spring of 2021, and it has at this moment moved up to 60% of it's military near Ukraine. The build-up of forces has so far strengthened NATO unity, caused western weapon shipments to Ukraine and has generally lowered Russian standing wit the West. Withdrawing troops without gaining significant political gains will be very harmful to Putin's reputation and popularity. Therefore I assess that without major concessions from Western powers or Ukraine war is almost certain. At this time there is no sign of a diplomatic solution, and most nations have started withdrawing their diplomatic missions and citizens from Ukraine.

Given the question, the answer is difficult. Reason is does it count Russian "volunteers" or mercenaries to Luhansk, Donetsk. Putin needs a win to extract himself from a problem of his own making, principally for nationalistic reasons and personal ego. Large number of countries withdrawing embassy staff and reaction from financial markets suggests the probability of an attack is higher now (though how much higher is unclear). There are still political risk advisory firms like Signum who have said they aren't raising their estimates of conflict on today's events, and it's true that much of the news from today is consistent with alternative explanations (e.g. Russian disinformation designed to inspire fear and coerce the West and Kiev into more diplomatic concessions). On balance, I raised my estimate by 10%.
Biden has signaled he will NOT be sending US troops to aid with an evacuation, and has explicitly directed Americans abroad to leave pronto. An "oops" is going to happen.

There seems to be some interesting shuttle diplomacy going on with France that may persuade Putin to look for a way out of his threats, without invasion. I'm ticking down my % down just 5%.

The risk seems to be receding a bit. It's also likely that any clashes wouldn't be acknowledged, just like in the Donbas a few years ago the Russian soldiers were not wearing insignia and have never been admitted by the Russian government to have been there.

In my opinion, Putin's comments with Macron were relatively clear... He will invade Ukraine IF they join NATO. To stop that from happening, I believe he wants to make it obvious that he is extremely willing to do this, hence the troop build up and preparations.

Lowering my forecasting percentage from 90 because of recent news on talks fronted by Macron. Maybe he and the EU will be able to work something out. I still do not see this as likely however, as Putin seems to have backed himself into a corner. Meaning he won't back down for fear of looking weak. Perhaps they can do a deal for reversing sanctions already leveled upon Russia. However this would also set a bad precedent. I'm unsure how the West can win here without Ukraine losing something.
While the momentum towards conflict has diminished slightly, the situation remains tense, I give it a 50/50 chance.

There seems to be some diplomatic hemming and hawing on the Ukraine issue from the Russian side. They have at times indicated their displeasure with the U.S. response to their list of concessions, and then backtracked and claimed that their declaration of the inadequacy of the State dept.'s response was misinterpreted. Despite this, their actions, primarily the positioning of Russian troops along the border is a costly signal that they are seriously considering invasion in the near term.
The recent troop movement appears to be unnecessary if Putin's intent is to bluff.
I think an invasion into the Donbas is as far as an invasion would go. Why I'm at 28%:

Adjusting to reflect other forecasts - specifically the one linked below - Supers saying there is a ~30% chance a NATO and/or a NATO member will accuse Russian national military forces of invading Ukraine. If that ~30% becomes reality it would be hard to not imagine at least 3 fatalities.

Increasing my probability slightly. I worry I have overestimated the likelihood that Russian actions have been a negotiating tactic this whole time. This report from FP made me rethink my position: https://foreignpolicy.com/2022/01/31/poll-russia-ukraine-invasion-crisis-biden-response/

(Love that this is posted by Dr. Strangelove, btw.) At this stage, the combination of negotiations and posturing are both encouraging, because neither side is fully committing to aggressive actions. But September is a long ways away, and it's easy for mistakes to happen, or priorities to change.

The diplomatic conflict between the U.S. and Russia seems to be heating up, neither sides appear to be able to facilitate meaningful dialogue. Russia also is ramping up its placement of troops along Ukrainian borders. U.S. is also sending troops likely for non-combat support. All of these factors seem to elevate the level of risk of conflict breaking out.
Revising downwards at least as long as talks are ongoing.

There is more and more talk of weeks and months more of negotiations and dialog. Winter is not that long. I now assess it to be slightly more likely than not that there will be no “official” fighting between national armies, but it’s still close to a coin toss given the heightened state of tensions…there is more than enough room for a mistake or miscalculation at multiple levels (on either side) to trigger fighting. If it happens, this will probably be the dumbest, most unnecessary war ever since the US invaded Iraq, and I’m still very much hoping that it can be avoided. In that case all involved would win.
Ukraine playing down these threats, as well as other western european powers.

Russia and the United States seem intent on making Ukraine a confrontational region/issue. Putin will not back down and allow himself to be seen as weak. The United States and it's allies won't back down for fear of emboldening Russia even further, and what backing down would mean to other Eastern European NATO allies. Ukraine itself is also poised to vigorously defend itself.
The increasing amount of troops in the area heightens the risk of a lethal confrontation before September 15, 2022.

The intense build up and readiness on both sides + weapons supplied by NATO will require a very high degree of discipline not to erupt into an event that satisfies the question. One missile or artillery shell hitting its mark would satisfy the question. I am thinking about what it would require to move away from 100%.

I think Putin is getting too many strategic benefits from the status quo (intra-EU acrimony, intra-NATO disagreements, and economic harm to Ukraine) to actual invade Donbass. He may stir things up more with 'un-affiliated militias', but I think he will avoid any confrontation between 'national military forces and/or law enforcement' like the plague.
Russian forces can’t stay masses on the U border forever.
The question is specific on what has to happen...I am leaning more towards "no" now with the probability of something more difficult to prove with "facts."
Assuming heavy bias on my part, therefore treating this as unlikely but essentially close to a tossup.
Ukraina would rather accept Russian protection (similarly to Belarus) under pressure of "imminent" war.

The fact that we in the U.S. have recently seen stories in the press about how it may not be all that bad makes me think that there is some official behind-the-scenes pushback against all the angst about the Russian buildup. So in the immediate future, it may be that we'll see a gradual easing of the frantic press reports about Russian military dispositions. We'll see what happens during the joint military maneuvers in Belarus in February. If nothing happens then, my odds will fall drastically.
While I believe the probability of a full scale Russian invasion is less than 50 percent I believe the odds of a skirmish of some type is more likely.

Reports today in the press that the call between Pres. Biden and Ukranian Pres. Zelensky "did not go well". A surprising turn a week after over 90 tons of US military equipment were delivered to Ukraine. Biden warns of significant build up in the last 24 hours along the Ukranian borders, including delivery of blood supplies and medical materials. But Zelensky warned the US and NATO that his intelligence officers disagree with their assessment and that there is no imminent danger. Zelensky went as far as blaming the US for affecting its economy with the panic of an imminent attack that they have created. Zelensky also said he was confident that the Russian threat is not as severe as some are making it out to be. “If you only look at the satellites, you will see the increase of troops. You can’t assess whether this is a threat, an attack or a simple rotation.” Another point of contention is Zelensky asking the US to impose sanctions on Russia and Putin now while Biden says sanctions will be imposed if Russia invades.
In my view, it is going to be not that risky win against the crowd.

Really useful analysis here: https://kyivindependent.com/national/center-for-defense-strategies-how-probable-is-large-scale-war-in-ukraine-analysis/?cn-reloaded=1 In summary: full-scale invasion into large parts of Ukraine unlikely, but increase in activities such as terrorist attacks and occupation of strategic territory a real possibility.

There’s a lot that could happen. Reports that Russia is moving missiles into range makes me think this could be more of an air campaign. It’s also reported that the Iron Dome antimissile system has been moved to Ukraine, so who knows what could happen. That would definitely make sense for Russia to do an air war when you think about the logistics of having to do a ground war, which really would be a nightmare for Russia. I’m therefor moving this up to a higher probability at least for the next few months. That said, it’s reported that tub diplomats are still talking so I think there’s a lot more uncertainty than the crowd believes: https://www.nytimes.com/2022/01/21/world/europe/ukraine-russia-us-blinken-lavrov.html

Today, the US Embassy in Kyiv asks State Dept. to authorize departure of nonessential personnel. Sec of State Blinken met with Russia's foreign minister Lavrov on Friday, Jan 21 and, as per his own words, "stressed that Russia has two choices: Diplomacy and de-escalation or massive costs to Russia. Our strong preference is to pursue the path of diplomacy." Hours after that meeting, Blinken tweeted: "The United States and its allies and partners are standing together to expedite security assistance to Ukraine. We are utilizing all available security cooperation tools to help Ukraine bolster its defenses in the face of Russian aggression. I expedited and authorized and we fully endorse transfers of defensive equipment @NATO Allies are providing to Ukraine to strengthen its ability to defend itself against Russia’s unprovoked and irresponsible aggression" adding this link https://kaitseministeerium.ee/en/news/baltic-defence-ministers-issue-joint-statement-sending-weapons-ukraine A few hours later he tweeted: "Spoke with Foreign Minister @DmytroKuleba to coordinate closely with Ukraine, as Allies and partners work to deter further Russian aggression. Ukraine has our unwavering support, and we will impose severe costs on Russia for any further military incursion."

Just taking into account recent events. The Embassy evacuation really points to this being a deliberate buildup and not some psy-op or bluff.

Although the most recent official UN OSCE SMM to Ukraine report has not yet been released, the number of ceasefire violations during the past 20 days (~3500) is a almost a third lower than the number of ceasefire violations in the preceding 20 days (5080). For world peace, this is a good sign, I think. As the political rhetoric goes up, the commanders on the ground grow more cautious.

Russia has an obsession with Ukraine as seen throughout its history, most recently evidenced with the annexation of Crimea in 2014. Putin cements power with foreign conquests and will be looking to Eastern Europe for more conquest goals. Unless the West presents a strong united front with drastic consequences for a Russian invasion, there is a significant chance Russia will attempt to carve out at least the eastern half of Ukraine.
news of Russia planting false flag events is troubling

I think this conflict is fundamentally a symptom of zero-sum, great power competition. Despite the reticence of NATO members to allow Ukraine membership, on the basis of it's open-door policy and the possibility of expansion in other European countries like Sweden and Finland, it seems likely that the alliance will spread ever closer to Russian borders. Russia clearly views this as a threat and consequently is doubling down on its attempts to preserve and expand its own influence in the post-soviet sphere. The U.S. is also clearly not willing to make a credible commitment to actions that would prevent further annexation or occupation. In light of the strategic context, the interests of each party, and their willingness to commit to military action in the area, I think it is very likely that Russia moves to further their grip on Ukraine, invariably causing fatalities in the process. They appear to be posed to do it well in advance of the deadline listed in the question.
I'll up my odds on the off-chance that Washington actually knows what it's talking about in this instance.
Switching to favor this. Seems like there are just a lot of signs that they're preparing for something.

Yes, with the escalating nature of Putin's remarks, it looks like diplomacy in the Ukraine is not going well. It seems likely Russia provokes something and then uses misinformation to place blame on the Ukraine or its allies.
This is likely since there is a build-up of Russian troops at the Ukraine border. Moreover, why would Putin expend all those resources for nothing to happen?
"British military aircraft rapidly supplying weapons to Ukraine" https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/british-aircraft-transporting-anti-armour-weapons-to-ukraine/
Adjusting up here to my gut- at this point it just "feels" more likely than not.
There is a probabilities of some kinds of shooting at the border by military due to the tension or provocations by groups or individual

As Russian forces have been fighting in the Donbas since 2014 and causing causatives at least monthly ever since, and signs are that things are heating up rather than cooling down, I place the value very high. If the question is whether declared and avowed Russian forces had a clash, I would put the chances more around 30%.
Putin didn't put all those troops there for them to just go home having achieved nothing. But achieving something doesn't necessarily mean bloodshed in Ukraine.

Here's the problem for the West as I see it: I don't think Russia wants to conquer and annex Ukraine. I think what Putin wants in to link up the Russian-controlled enclave in the Donbas with Crimea, which will also give some strategic depth to Russian holdings in Ukraine. he also wants to permanently keep the rump Ukraine as a buffer state between Russia and NATO.

The Russian buildup of forces along the Ukraine border is intensifying. The potential miscalculation is rising and the situation in Ukraine may result in the confluence of sufficient Russian forces to take advantage of a humanitarian or internal security concern for a limited occupation and small-scale battles resulting in fatalities.
Going up based in part on this ( https://twitter.com/Sara__Firth/status/1482981864679821313 ), which indicates more willingness by Russia to do something beyond their border.

I have for a long time been rather sceptical of more alarmist analysis, as the experts I personally find to be more convincing have also been quite conservative in that regard. This major revision to my initial forecast reflects a more careful reading of the question, combined with some more time spent actually reading up on this topic (I'm no expert on Russia or on military topics in general). Unfortunately, this seems to be one of those questions where the casually read statement invites one (me at least!) to forecast on a question that is not actually the one being asked. My new viewpoint centers on the specifics of the wording: "...BETWEEN the NATIONAL MILITARY FORCES...of RUSSIA AND UKRAINE...".

This is a complex question to forecast, as there are significant deterrents to military action on both sides that would result in the deaths stated in the question. Russia has to be concerned about reputation and pressure on the world stage, US/European support for Ukraine as a counter balance to aggression, etc. Ukraine has to be concerned about poking the bear and provoking a reaction if it employs kinetic force. Nonetheless, Ukraine is receiving increased military support from others, including Turkey (armed drones that recently destroyed some Russia artillery (https://usukraine.org/news/articles/ukraine-uses-turkish-drone-for-the-first-time-warns-of-renewed-buildup-of-russian-troops-on-border/NjA4MjE=) ). Recently, a group of Ukrainian combat veterans were warmly welcomed to Washington, DC. (https://usukraine.org/news/articles/stronger-together/NjA4MTM=/). U.S. support for Ukraine remains strong and serves as a deterrent to Russia. Thus, tensions continue to build like magma heating under the surface of a volcano. WHEN is event described in the question going to happen (or when will a series of events add up to 3 deaths)? Sadly, I think the threshold of three service member deaths total will be achieved before the conflict is finally resolved at some point in the unforeseeable/difficult to see future. So, the question is therefore isolated to timing. Will the threshold death count be reached before or after the question deadline? I have gotten zapped on timing before (timing of delivery of the articles of impeachment for Trump, and timing of the death of RBG). I was accurate in the substance, but slightly off on the timing (and got hammered on my accuracy score). So the answer has to be yes (i.e. the probability cannot be zero, but that seems obvious, right?). But, also something close to the current 11% also seems overconfident, given the 10 months before the question closes. Remember, "There are decades where nothing happens; and there are weeks where decades happen"--Vladimir Ilyich Lenin. Events can turn very quickly. I really hate close to 50% probabilities, as that is a coin flip and as a professional forecaster, means, "I dunno." Sometimes that is as good as you can get. You can't tell. There are 312 days until the question closes, this is close to the limits of accurate forecasting of geopolitical events. Thus, I think a wide range is justified early on, then will narrow with time, and thoughtful consideration of new information as it becomes available. If I were to go narrower at this point, 1) I don't see facts or informations to support a narrower range, and 2) that narrower range would be speculative, or a guess. Some forecasters get lucky on guesses and claim to be "right,", but that is not effective forecasting in the long run.
